```class Solution {
    public int nextBeautifulNumber(int n) {
        while (true) {
            n++;
            String str = String.valueOf(n);
            boolean balanced = true;
            int[] count = new int[10];
            for (char c : str.toCharArray()) {
                count[c - '0']++;
            }
            for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
                if (count[i] != i) {
                    balanced = false;
                    break;
                }
            }
            if (balanced) {
                return n;
            }
        }
    }
}```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(log10(n))
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution uses a while loop to increment the number until it finds the smallest numerically balanced number strictly greater than n. It converts the number to a string and counts the occurrences of each digit. Then it checks if the count of each digit is equal to the digit itself. If it is, the number is numerically balanced and the function returns it. The time complexity is O(log10(n)) because the number of digits in the number is proportional to the logarithm of the number. The space complexity is O(1) because the space used does not grow with the input size.

